# Cursor Rules for LocaMaster Pro V2

## Project Context
This is a Next.js 15 equipment rental management system with TypeScript, Tailwind CSS v4, and Shadcn/ui. The system manages equipment rentals, contracts, billing, customers, and provides comprehensive business management for rental companies.

## Code Standards
- Always use TypeScript with strict mode enabled
- Implement proper error handling with try-catch blocks
- Follow OWASP Top 10 security guidelines religiously
- Validate all inputs with Zod schemas before processing
- Use async/await pattern instead of promises when possible
- Keep components small (<150 lines) and focused on single responsibility
- Use proper TypeScript generics and avoid 'any' type

## Security First (CRITICAL)
- Never expose sensitive data (passwords, tokens, financial data) in logs or responses
- Always sanitize user inputs to prevent XSS attacks
- Implement rate limiting on all API endpoints (100 req/min)
- Use HTTPS everywhere in production
- Configure security headers (CSP, HSTS, X-Frame-Options)
- Validate permissions before allowing access to sensitive operations
- Implement audit logging for all critical actions (billing, contracts, user management)

## Architecture Patterns
- Use domain-driven design for feature organization
- Implement repository pattern for data access
- Use factory pattern for complex object creation (contracts, invoices)
- Apply SOLID principles in class design
- Implement proper separation of concerns

## Equipment Rental Business Logic
- Always check equipment availability before creating rentals
- Implement proper contract state management (draft, active, completed, cancelled)
- Calculate rental prices based on duration, equipment type, and customer tier
- Handle equipment maintenance schedules and availability
- Implement late return penalties and damage assessments
- Support multiple pricing models (daily, weekly, monthly rates)

## Performance Requirements
- Implement lazy loading for heavy components (equipment lists, customer grids)
- Use React.memo() for components that re-render frequently
- Optimize bundle size - analyze imports and remove unused dependencies
- Implement virtual scrolling for large datasets (1000+ items)
- Use Next.js Image component for all images with proper optimization
- Configure caching strategies (API responses, static assets)
- Monitor Core Web Vitals (LCP < 2.5s, FID < 100ms, CLS < 0.1)

## API Design
- Use RESTful conventions with proper HTTP methods
- Implement consistent error response format
- Return standard envelope: { success: boolean, data?: T, error?: ErrorObject }
- Use proper HTTP status codes (200, 201, 400, 401, 404, 500)
- Implement pagination for all list endpoints
- Add request/response validation middleware
- Document all endpoints with OpenAPI/Swagger comments

## Database/Storage Patterns
- Use Prisma ORM for type-safe database operations
- Implement proper relationship handling (equipment -> rentals -> customers)
- Use transactions for multi-table operations (contract creation, billing)
- Implement soft deletes for audit trail
- Use proper indexing for frequently queried fields
- Handle concurrent access with optimistic locking

## Testing Requirements
- Write unit tests for all business logic functions
- Implement integration tests for API endpoints  
- Add E2E tests for critical user flows (create rental, generate invoice)
- Maintain minimum 80% code coverage
- Test error scenarios and edge cases
- Mock external dependencies properly

## Component Development
- Start every component with proper TypeScript interfaces
- Implement proper loading states and error boundaries
- Add accessibility attributes (aria-labels, roles, etc.)
- Use Shadcn/ui components as base, customize with Tailwind
- Implement proper form validation with React Hook Form + Zod
- Add proper error handling and user feedback

## File Organization
```
src/
├── app/                 # Next.js app router
├── components/
│   ├── ui/             # Reusable UI components
│   ├── features/       # Business domain components
│   └── layout/         # Layout components
├── lib/
│   ├── auth/           # Authentication logic
│   ├── db/             # Database/storage layer
│   ├── validations/    # Zod schemas
│   └── utils/          # Utility functions
├── hooks/              # Custom React hooks
└── types/              # TypeScript type definitions
```

## Before Committing
1. Run TypeScript check: `npm run type-check` (must pass)
2. Run linter: `npm run lint` (must pass)
3. Run tests: `npm run test` (must pass with >80% coverage)
4. Check bundle size: `npm run analyze` (initial bundle <500KB)
5. Verify security: `npm audit` (no high/critical vulnerabilities)
6. Update documentation if APIs or major features changed
7. Ensure all environment variables are properly configured
8. Verify all database migrations are included

## AI Assistant Behavior
- Always consider security implications of any code changes
- Suggest performance optimizations proactively
- Maintain consistent code style throughout the project
- Update tests when changing existing functionality
- Document complex business logic with clear comments
- Implement proper error handling for all async operations
- Validate all user inputs before processing
- Consider accessibility in all UI components
- Suggest better TypeScript types when 'any' is used
- Recommend proper caching strategies for data fetching

## Business Domain Knowledge
- Equipment can have multiple states: available, rented, maintenance, retired
- Contracts can span multiple equipment items with different rental periods
- Billing cycles are configurable (daily, weekly, monthly cutoffs)
- Late returns incur penalty fees based on equipment value and delay duration
- Equipment maintenance schedules affect availability
- Customer credit limits impact rental approvals
- Seasonal pricing variations may apply to certain equipment categories
- Insurance requirements vary by equipment type and rental duration

## Error Handling Patterns
```typescript
// Standard error boundary implementation
class FeatureErrorBoundary extends ErrorBoundary {
  fallback = ({ error, resetErrorBoundary }) => (
    <ErrorFallback error={error} onReset={resetErrorBoundary} />
  );
}

// API error handling
try {
  const result = await apiCall();
  return { success: true, data: result };
} catch (error) {
  logger.error('Operation failed', { error, context });
  return { 
    success: false, 
    error: { 
      code: 'OPERATION_FAILED', 
      message: 'User-friendly message' 
    } 
  };
}
```

## Performance Monitoring
- Implement Core Web Vitals tracking
- Monitor API response times and error rates
- Track bundle size and loading performance
- Set up alerts for performance regressions
- Use React DevTools Profiler for optimization
- Monitor memory usage in long-running sessions
